By Joyce Remi- Bababyeju Abuja ( Sundiatapost) – The Coronavirus pandemic which took the world by storm has taken a new dimension as the number of affected cares worldwide skyrockets to a frightening figure of 105,621 cases, the World Health Organisation, according to the WHO Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) Dashboard. Since the virus first surfaced in the Chinese village of Wuhan it has spread like wildfire across the world. It has become an outbreak it was declared a Public Health Emergency of International Concern on 30 January 2020 and on 11 February 2020, WHO announced a name for the new coronavirus disease making the WHO Director General, Tedros Adhanom Ghegbreyesus to pronounce it a world pandemic. As at today (Thursday) the Nigeria Centre for Disease Control, NCDC, has confirmed that Nigeria has recorded 13,873 cases with a total deaths of 382. Worldwide, according to WHO Dashboard on COVID-19, the world has recorded 105,621 deaths, 7,273, 958 confirmed cases and 413,372 deaths. United States of America 739,503confirmed cases Brazil 502,436confirmed cases Russian Federation 290,147confirmed cases The United Kingdom 286,579confirmed cases India 242,280confirmed cases Spain 235,763confirmed cases Italy 203,736confirmed cases Peru 185,416confirmed cases Germany 177,938confirmed cases Iran (Islamic Republic of) 173,036confirmed cases Turkey 151,145confirmed cases France Source: WHO By Joyce Remi- Babayeju The novel COVID-19 pandemic in Nigeria has taken a new twist as the country records 260 fresh confirmed cases of the virus in 19 states, with Abia State leading with 67, Kano and Sokoto states recording just two cases each. The latest 260 new confirmed cases… June 8, 2020 In "Health" By Cecilia Ologunagba Abuja - The World Health Organisation (WHO) says 44 countries in Africa can now test for COVID-19. The UN’s health agency disclosed this on Friday in its official twitter account @WHOAFRO. The WHO said at the start of the outbreak only two could do so. “As COVID